I explored the code by searching `Publish(` and `Subscribe(` across `internal/`, then reading the core modules: `internal/event/bus.go`, `bag.go`, `task.go`, `achievement.go`, `equipment.go`, `signin.go`, `mail.go`, plus bootstrap and command flow in `internal/player/manager.go` and `internal/server/server.go`. That established the static event graph and showed that the `dual` profile uses queued commands plus `next` for stepwise execution.

Runtime verification matched most of the code graph. Adding item `2001` triggered `item.added -> task 3001 completed -> achievement 4001 unlocked -> achievement mail sent`. Adding item `2002` twice triggered `task 3002 completed -> achievement 4002 unlocked`, and then incorrectly unlocked collector `4003`. Checking in day 1 triggered `signin.claimed -> mail sent with attachment`. Adding `3001` and `3002` triggered auto-equip for weapon and armor, then `equip.success -> fully_equipped 4004 -> achievement mail sent`.

The main anomalies were around dead-end events. `mail.claimed` has no subscriber, so claiming a reward mail consumes the attachment without adding the item to Bag. `signin.reward` also has no subscriber, and `ClaimReward` can be executed repeatedly, producing logs only. The collector achievement logic is also semantically wrong: it unlocked because two achievements were already unlocked, not because any collector threshold was actually met.
